<br>
I was using the 49 Fire Pet to tank, buffed with Heroism, Symbol and Shield of Words..  No matter what, the mob would constantly beat on the necro pet (39 spell) and ignore mine.  Even if we waited until the mob was at 80%, 60%, 20% health, and then we sent in the necro pet, it will instantly switch to it.  Is this working as intended?  Maybe this is nothing new..<br>
<br>
Coinendently I was duoing with a 53 Enchanter and we had the same problem, the mob would ignore my fire pet. <p><br><hr>
<br>Talveran Shadowbomb
<br>Level 51 Mage
<br>Ayonae Ro</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/udordolafhealsmith.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dordolaf Healsmith</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#333333>(8/8/02 3:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=626.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Pet Aggro Bug or Working as Intended (tm)?</span><hr size=1> Unfortunatley this is always the case.  A mob will always beat on the weakest pet.  I fought my way up with a nec through 53 and through out our battles the mob will never beat on mine =(.  Ohh well...when his pet gets low he backs it off and lets mine tank for a while.  Or we fear kite.  Hope this helps =)<br>
<br>
 <p>Dordolaf Healsmith<br>
Cleric Of The 54th Season <br>
<br>
Dumsday Obstructor<br>
Magician of The 52nd Season <br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=izudin>Izudin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 63<br> <font color=#333333>(8/8/02 6:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=626.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Distance</span><hr size=1> From what I have read here this is more a distance based thing.<br>
<br>
Mage pets have a lot larger hit radius than necro (or enc) pets, which means if you send your pet to attack a mob it will stay further from it than a necro pet would. And since aggro is partly distance based, the mob will always turn on the necro or enc pet.<br>
<br>
To avoid this it was suggested that you pull a mob onto the (mage) pet, so it is the closest thing to it.<br>
<br>
I haven't tried this personally, but it sounds reasonable.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uadonhiram.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Adonhiram</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 84<br> <font color=#333333>(8/8/02 7:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=626.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Distance</span><hr size=1> Both points are true. A standard mob (some special &quot;intelligent&quot; mobs might have specificities though in aggro rules) facing pets, with no PC in melee range, will :<br>
<br>
- tend to prefer the lower level pet (same aggro rules as with PCs, the level 50 warrior fighting the same mob with his level 60 warrior buddy will, at least at beginning of the fight, be preferred by the mob even if his damage output is obviously lower) ;<br>
<br>
- tend to prefer the &quot;closer&quot; pet, id est skellies have shorter melee range than elementals ;<br>
<br>
- if you use an earth pet (and DON'T do it if you group with a necro EVEN if you are not fear kiting), whatever is the aggro level of both pets, a rooted mob will always hit the pet with the shorter melee range, it means, the pet which it considers to be the closest (standard root aggro rule), whatever is its hate level towards this closest pet.<br>
<br>
Point 1 and Point 2 are of course not absolute rules as you must take into consideration the main factor of hate which is the amount of damage each pet inflicts to the mob, so mob will switch targets of course.<br>
<br>
If you have a skelly and an elemental, prefer air pet as stuns are huge aggro and might help to better 'dispatch' the targets. Your necro buddy will love you, and air pets, due to high ac, can take a better beating than skellies. Necro should always turn taunt off when he duos with a mage in a non fear kiting situation, except if you wish for some reason the skelly to be the primary target of the mob.<br>
<br>
Elemental Greetings :-) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uansifiretosser.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ansi Firetosser</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 496<br> <font color=#333333>(8/8/02 12:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=626.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Distance</span><hr size=1> Dordolaf said...<br>
